The paper proposes a novel convolutional neural network for fine-grained classification of human actions and attributes. This involves detecting small and inconspicuous objects and features, which suggests computer vision (cs.CV) as the most likely sub-category. The paper also mentions training a CNN (DeepPattern) that learns discriminative patch groups, which involves feature learning and patch clustering, suggesting machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) as likely sub-categories. The paper validates their method on challenging datasets, which suggests multimedia (cs.MM) and information retrieval (cs.IR) as possible sub-categories.
